  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The National Health Service (NHS) stop smoking service at the Central Lancashire NHS Trust
      serves a diverse population of smokers, with a very good quit rate and high standards.
      However, clinical experience predicts that some clients are unlikely to succeed through the
      NHS smoking cessation program. This special population has difficulty quitting for a variety
      of reasons. Some relapse over the course of the following two years and return repeatedly to
      the service. Others, for instance those with health problems, may be highly motivated to
      quit, but unable to resist their cravings. The purpose of this study is to determine if EFT
      makes a difference in quit rates with the most challenging population of clients.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
